se leaders entered Cold War alliances, distanced themselves from progressive civil rights and anti-colonial movements, and turned a blind eye to human rights abuses in Israel. In The Threshold of Dissent, Marjorie N. Feld instead shows that today’s vociferous arguments among American Jews over Israel and Zionism are but the newest chapter in a fraught history that stretches from the nineteenth century. Drawing on rich archival research and examining wide-ranging intellectual currents—from the Reform movement and the Yiddish left to anti-colonialism and Jewish feminism—Feld explores American Jewish critics of Zionism and Israel from the 1880s to the 1980s. The book argues that the tireless policing of contrary perspectives led each generation of dissenters to believe that it was the first to question unqualified support for Israel. The Threshold of Dissent positions contemporary critics within a century-long debate about the priorities of the American Jewish community, one which holds profound implications for inclusion in American Jewish communal life and for American Jews’ participation in coalitions working for justice.At a time when American Jewish support for Israel has been diminishing, The Threshold of Dissent uncovers a deeper—and deeply contested—history of intracommunal debate over Zionism among American Jews.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aJewszUnited StatesxAttitudes toward Israel. 0aJewszUnited StatesxPolitics and government. 0aZionismzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  a1982 Lebanon War.  a1983 March on Washington.  a2022 Israeli elections.  aAmerican Council for Judaism.  aAmerican Jewish Committee.  aAmerican Jews.  aAnti-Zionism.  aAnti-colonialism.  aBlack antisemitism.  aBreira.  aHannah Arendt.  aHenry Hurwitz.  aIfNotNow.  aIsr